It has been difficult to categorize many of the sonnets.  For example, should every poem that includes the word "eye" or "eyes" be marked as having "eye" imagery?  For some mentions, clearly so: In sonnet __, the opening line is "My mistress's eyes are nothing lik ethe sun".  This clearly evokes an image of a beloved's face and eyes.  (Find another example if possible.)  However, sonnet 27 mentions how the beloved keeps "my drooping eyelids open wide".  Is this a mention of eyes in the same way as the first?  It doesn't so much describe or call to mind a visual description of a person's eyes as signify that the speaker can't sleep (although it is a visual image).  Beyond that, the sun is often described as the "eye of heaven", the "golden eye", or similar.  Would we count these as eye images?  
The assigning of categories is a "reverse" searching process.  I read a sonnet and decide whether it fits into certain categories.  However, the reader of this website will go in the opposite direction.  In their "forward" process, they will click on a category ("eyes") and expect to see sonnets with descriptions of a person's eyes.  If the eye is used as a methaphor for something else, like the sun, or a window, or a painter, I have left that out of the category.  The "in between" case of dropping eyelids open wide I have included, because it is at least a specific image of a person's eyes doing something.
Other tough cases were things like "concepts."  For example, numerous sonnets have references to widows.  A widow is a person, a woman whose husband has died.  Is this better considered a "theme" or an "image"?  It's not really a specific physical entity, like most of the images.  It's conceptual.  However, it doesn't seem to fit the theme category, which has more to do with the ideas used in the poems, the predominant emotions.  Perhaps concepts could be considered a third category.  However, the site starts to grow too elaborate.  That may be more categorization than a reader expects, or could find useful.  It also feels like a weaker category.  What else would go in "concepts?"  Motherhood, wifehood?  Not sure.
